#let images = (
  "figure-18.1": (
    caption: [Boundaries of some communities are clearly defined, as shown by chaparral vegetation at higher elevations, grassland on lower slopes, and live oaks in moister valleys in southern California. This illustrates how physical and biological factors can create distinct community borders.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-10-57.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.2": (
    caption: [Communities are often named after their most conspicuous members or physical characteristics. Examples include a ponderosa pine community, a riparian forest community, and a young deciduous forest community, each dominated by different plant species and environmental conditions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-11-22.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.3": (
    caption: [Closed community structure is distinguished from open community structure by the presence of ecotones. The diagram shows hypothetical distributions of species along an environmental gradient, with closed communities forming distinct assemblages and open communities showing independent species distributions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-11-43.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.4": (
    caption: [Ecotones are often associated with abrupt changes in the physical environment. This coastal scene shows seaweeds extending only to the high-tide mark, with a barren zone between the high tide and spruce forest due to wave action and salt spray, resulting in a sharp boundary in vegetation.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-11-54.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.5": (
    caption: [Differences in soil conditions may result in ecotones. The figure shows replacement of plant species and changes in soil element concentrations across a boundary between non-serpentine and serpentine soils in southwestern Oregon. Some species are restricted to specific soils, others to the ecotone, and some are unresponsive to soil chemistry.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-12-27.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.6": (
    caption: [The distributions of plant species may be determined by factors other than physiological tolerance of soil characteristics. Seedlings of lodgepole pine, pygmy cypress, and Sargent cypress were grown on acid, normal, and serpentine soils, revealing that some species grow well on soils outside their natural range, suggesting other factors restrict their distributions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-12-43.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.7": (
    caption: [Species that occur together at a particular place may have different geographic distributions. The figure shows that none of the twelve tree species in eastern Kentucky have the same geographic range, highlighting the independent evolutionary backgrounds and ecological relationships of co-occurring species.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-13-02.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.8": (
    caption: [Dominant tree species of the Great Smoky Mountains show distinct but overlapping distributions along gradients of elevation and soil moisture. Red oak, beech, and white oak each have greatest abundance at different points but extend into other forest types, illustrating the continuum concept in community structure.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-13-25.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.9": (
    caption: [Gradient analyses reveal open community structures. Whittaker's study in the Santa Catalina Mountains recorded plant species distributions along a soil moisture gradient, showing unique ecological distributions and peaks of abundance scattered along the gradient, shaped by adaptations and species interactions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-13-46.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.10": (
    caption: [Tropical forests harbor the greatest species richness of any communities. The aerial photograph of Barro Colorado Island, Panama, demonstrates the high diversity of tree species, with more than 300 species found among 240,000 individuals on a 50-hectare plot.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-14-00.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.11": (
    caption: [Different communities of similar species richness may have different food web structures. The intertidal mudflat community has a simple food web, while the plant–insect–parasitoid community is more complex, with several omnivorous species and more feeding links among species.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-14-22.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.12": (
    caption: [Increasing species richness is associated with increasing food web complexity. Food web diagrams for invertebrate communities in Nepenthes pitcher plants show more trophic levels and guilds, and longer food chains, but similar numbers of feeding links per species as species richness increases.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-14-50.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.13": (
    caption: [Experimental elimination of keystone consumers demonstrates their controlling influence on species diversity. Insecticide treatment prevented beetle outbreaks, allowing goldenrod to dominate and shade out other species, reducing diversity compared to unsprayed control plots.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-15-02.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.14": (
    caption: [Ecologists use three approaches to depicting trophic relationships: connectedness webs (feeding relationships), energy flow webs (quantified energy flux), and functional webs (influence on population growth rates). The diagrams show these approaches applied to a rocky intertidal zone community.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-15-25.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.15": (
    caption: [Fox predation on seabirds transforms plant communities on subarctic islands. On Buldir Island (no foxes), grasses dominate; on Ogangan Island (foxes present), shrubs and forbs dominate, illustrating how top predators can indirectly affect plant community composition through trophic cascades.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-15-41.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.16": (
    caption: [Environmental perturbation can cause delayed responses in community functioning. Spring watering of grassland plots increased production and shifted dominance to nitrogen-fixing forbs, but after several years, grasses regained dominance and species richness remained reduced, showing resilience and long-term effects of disturbance.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-16-06.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.17": (
    caption: [The resilience of communities increases with diversity. Laboratory microcosms with more species showed greater resilience (rate of return to control biomass) under low nutrient availability, suggesting that species diversity can enhance recovery from disturbance.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-16-26.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.18": (
    caption: [Removal of organisms in a New England rocky intertidal zone community results in replacement by one of several possible new communities. Clearing rockweed led to dominance by barnacles or brown algae, depending on exposure and patch size, illustrating alternative stable states.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-16-49.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.19": (
    caption: [The trophic structure of a community may be determined by bottom-up or top-down control. The diagram shows how addition of trophic levels and changes in control mechanisms can result in trophic cascades and alternating relative biomass among levels.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-17-12.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.20": (
    caption: [Primary consumer density shows the effects of both bottom-up and top-down influences. In natural lakes, zooplankton and phytoplankton densities are positively correlated (bottom-up control), but adding fish reduces zooplankton and increases phytoplankton (top-down control).],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-17-46.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.21": (
    caption: [Community structure and its response to changes in productivity depend on the number of trophic levels. Microcosm experiments show that adding nutrients increases biomasses at most trophic levels, but adding fish (a fourth level) reduces zooplankton and increases producers, demonstrating both bottom-up and top-down effects.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-18-25.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.22": (
    caption: [Change in nutrient levels can switch a marine community between alternative stable states. High nutrient levels favor large diatoms and direct feeding by copepods; low nutrient levels favor small algae and indirect effects via ciliates, with jellyfish predation further influencing community structure.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-18-52.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.23": (
    caption: [The presence or absence of fish in ponds influences dragonfly densities. Ponds with fish produced fewer larval and adult dragonflies than ponds without fish, demonstrating the impact of predators on lower trophic levels.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-19-17.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.24": (
    caption: [The presence or absence of fish in ponds can influence nearby terrestrial communities. Pollinators paid more visits to St. John’s wort shrubs near ponds with fish, showing how aquatic food web changes can affect terrestrial pollination.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-19-40.png"
  ),
  "figure-18.25": (
    caption: [Fish have indirect effects on the populations of several species in and around ponds. The diagram shows direct and indirect effects through a trophic cascade, with fish reducing dragonflies, increasing pollinators, and improving plant reproductive success.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-21-16-20-13.png"
  )
)
